<span id="fn_938"></span>[168:939](2040204.htm#fr_938.md) <span
id="xiv.ii.vi-p24.2"></span>

<span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25"></span> This extract discloses to us (in
connexion with the passages from Dionysius Alex. here and in the *de
Sent. D.*) a remarkable anticipation of the Arian controversy in the
third century. 1. It appears that the very symbol of <span
class="Greek"><span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.2"></span>ἦ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.3"></span>ν ὅτε οὐκ ἦν</span>,
‘once He was not,’ was asserted or implied; vid. also the following
extract from Origen, §27. and Origen *Periarchon,* iv. 28. where mention
is also made of the <span class="Greek"><span
id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.5"></span>ἐ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.6"></span>ξ οὐκ ὄντων</span>, ‘out of nothing,’ which
was the Arian symbol in opposition to ‘of the substance.’ Allusions are
made besides, to ‘the Father not being always Father,’ *de Sent. D.* 15.
and ‘the Word being brought to be by the true Word, and Wisdom by the
true Wisdom;’ ibid. 25. 2. The same special text is used in defence of
the heresy, and that not at first sight an obvious one, which is found
among the Arians, <span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.8"></span>[Prov. viii.
22](../../../bib/kjv/pro008.htm#022.md)<span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.10"></span>.
3. The same texts were used by the Catholics, which occur in the Arian
controversy. e.g. [Deut. 32:6](../../../bib/kjv/deu032.htm#006.md), [Prov.
8:22](../../../bib/kjv/pro008.htm#022.md), [Ps.
110:3](../../../bib/kjv/psa110.htm#003.md), [Prov.
8:25](../../../bib/kjv/pro008.htm#025.md), [John
10:30](../../../bib/kjv/joh010.htm#030.md), [John
14:10](../../../bib/kjv/joh014.htm#010.md)<span
id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.12"></span>[Deut. xxxii.
6](../../../bib/kjv/deu032.htm#006.md)<span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.14"></span>.
against [Prov. viii. 22](../../../bib/kjv/pro008.htm#022.md)<span
id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.15"></span>. and such as [Ps. cx.
3](../../../bib/kjv/psa010.htm#003.md)<span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.16"></span>.
[Prov. viii. 25](../../../bib/kjv/pro008.htm#025.md)<span
id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.17"></span>. and the two [John x.
30](../../../bib/kjv/joh010.htm#030.md)<span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.18"></span>.
and xiv. 10. 4. The same Catholic symbols and statements are found, e.g.
‘begotten not made,’ ‘one in essence,’ ‘Trinity,’ <span
class="Greek"><span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.20"></span>ἀ</span><span
class="Greek"><span id="xiv.ii.vi-p25.21"></span>διαίρετον, ἄναρχον,
ἀειγενες</span>, ‘light from light,’ &c. Much might be said on this
circumstance, as forming part of the proof of the very early date of the
development and formation of the Catholic theology, which we are at
first sight apt to ascribe to the 4th and 5th centuries. \[But see
Introd. to *de Sent. Dion.*\]

